[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/low-rank-approximation] However, the Alternating Direction Method of Multipliers (ADMM) can be applied to solve the nonconvex problem with convex objective function, rank constraints and other convex constraints, and is thus suitable to solve our above problem.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/low-rank-approximation] Moreover, unlike the general nonconvex problems, ADMM will guarantee to converge a feasible solution as long as its dual variable converges in the iterations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In mathematics, and in particular linear algebra, the **Moore–Penrose inverse** ⁠ $A^{+}$ ⁠ of a matrix ⁠ A ⁠, often called the **pseudoinverse**, is the most widely known generalization of the inverse matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Moore in 1920, Arne Bjerhammar in 1951, and Roger Penrose in 1955.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Earlier, Erik Ivar Fredholm had introduced the concept of a pseudoinverse of integral operators in 1903.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The terms *pseudoinverse* and *generalized inverse* are sometimes used as synonyms for the Moore–Penrose inverse of a matrix, but sometimes applied to other elements of algebraic structures which share some but not all properties expected for an inverse element.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] A common use of the pseudoinverse is to compute a "best fit" (least squares) approximate solution to a system of linear equations that lacks an exact solution (see below under § Applications).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Another use is to find the minimum (Euclidean) norm solution to a system of linear equations with multiple solutions.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The pseudoinverse facilitates the statement and proof of results in linear algebra.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The pseudoinverse is defined for all rectangular matrices whose entries are real or complex numbers.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Given a rectangular matrix with real or complex entries, its pseudoinverse is unique.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] It can be computed using the singular value decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In the special case where ⁠ A ⁠ is a normal matrix (for example, a Hermitian matrix), the pseudoinverse ⁠ $A^{+}$ ⁠ annihilates the kernel of ⁠ A ⁠ and acts as a traditional inverse of ⁠ A ⁠ on the subspace orthogonal to the kernel.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In the following discussion, the following conventions are adopted.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] More specifically, $A^{+}A$ projects onto the image of $A^{T}$ (equivalently, the span of the rows of A ), and $AA^{+}$ projects onto the image of A (equivalently, the span of the columns of A ).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In fact, the above four conditions are fully equivalent to $A^{+}A$ and $AA^{+}$ being such orthogonal projections: $AA^{+}$ projecting onto the image of A implies $(AA^{+})A=A$ , and $A^{+}A$ projecting onto the image of $A^{T}$ implies $(A^{+}A)A^{T}=A^{T}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The pseudoinverse $A^{+}$ exists for any matrix $A\in \mathbb {K} ^{m\times n}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] If furthermore A is full rank, that is, its rank is ⁠ $\min\{m,n\}$ ⁠, then ⁠ $A^{+}$ ⁠ can be given a particularly simple algebraic expression.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In the more general case, the pseudoinverse can be expressed using the singular value decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Any matrix can be decomposed as $A=UDV^{*}$ for some isometries $U,V$ and diagonal nonnegative real matrix D .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The pseudoinverse can then be written as $A^{+}=VD^{+}U^{*}$ , where $D^{+}$ is the pseudoinverse of D and can be obtained by transposing the matrix and replacing the nonzero values with their multiplicative inverses.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] That this matrix satisfies the above requirement is directly verified observing that $AA^{+}=UU^{*}$ and $A^{+}A=VV^{*}$ , which are the projections onto image and support of A , respectively.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] As discussed above, for any matrix ⁠ A ⁠ there is one and only one pseudoinverse ⁠ $A^{+}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] A matrix satisfying only the first of the conditions given above, namely ${\textstyle AA^{+}A=A}$ , is known as a generalized inverse.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] If the matrix also satisfies the second condition, namely ${\textstyle A^{+}AA^{+}=A^{+}}$ , it is called a generalized *reflexive* inverse.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Generalized inverses always exist but are not in general unique.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Uniqueness is a consequence of the last two conditions.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Proofs for the properties below can be found at b:Topics in Abstract Algebra/Linear algebra.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The computation of the pseudoinverse is reducible to its construction in the Hermitian case.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] This can be proven by defining matrices $C=BA$ , $D=A(BA)^{+}$ , and checking that ⁠ D ⁠ is indeed a pseudoinverse for ⁠ C ⁠ by verifying that the defining properties of the pseudoinverse hold, when ⁠ A ⁠ is Hermitian and idempotent.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Finally, if ⁠ A ⁠ is an orthogonal projection matrix, then its pseudoinverse trivially coincides with the matrix itself, that is, $A^{+}=A$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] If we view the matrix as a linear map ⁠ $A:\mathbb {K} ^{n}\to \mathbb {K} ^{m}$ ⁠ over the field ⁠ $\mathbb {K}$ ⁠ then ⁠ $A^{+}:\mathbb {K} ^{m}\to \mathbb {K} ^{n}$ ⁠ can be decomposed as follows.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] We write ⁠ $\oplus$ ⁠ for the direct sum, ⁠ $\perp$ ⁠ for the orthogonal complement, ⁠ $\ker$ ⁠ for the kernel of a map, and ⁠ $\operatorname {ran}$ ⁠ for the image of a map.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Notice that $\mathbb {K} ^{n}=\left(\ker A\right)^{\perp }\oplus \ker A$ and $\mathbb {K} ^{m}=\operatorname {ran} A\oplus \left(\operatorname {ran} A\right)^{\perp }$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The restriction $A:\left(\ker A\right)^{\perp }\to \operatorname {ran} A$ is then an isomorphism.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In other words: To find ⁠ $A^{+}b$ ⁠ for given ⁠ b ⁠ in ⁠ $\mathbb {K} ^{m}$ ⁠, first project ⁠ b ⁠ orthogonally onto the range of ⁠ A ⁠, finding a point ⁠ $p(b)$ ⁠ in the range.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] This will be an affine subspace of ⁠ $\mathbb {K} ^{n}$ ⁠ parallel to the kernel of ⁠ A ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The element of this subspace that has the smallest length (that is, is closest to the origin) is the answer ⁠ $A^{+}b$ ⁠ we are looking for.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] It can be found by taking an arbitrary member of ⁠ $A^{-1}(\{p(b)\})$ ⁠ and projecting it orthogonally onto the orthogonal complement of the kernel of ⁠ A ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] This description is closely related to the minimum-norm solution to a linear system.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In contrast to ordinary matrix inversion, the process of taking pseudoinverses is not continuous: if the sequence ⁠ $\left(A_{n}\right)$ ⁠ converges to the matrix ⁠ A ⁠ (in the maximum norm or Frobenius norm, say), then ⁠ $(A_{n})^{+}$ ⁠ need not converge to ⁠ $A^{+}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Let $x\mapsto A(x)$ be a real-valued differentiable matrix function with constant rank in a neighborhood of a point ⁠ $x_{0}$ ⁠.
