[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] For a real-valued symmetric matrix, the Magnus-Neudecker derivative is established.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Since for invertible matrices the pseudoinverse equals the usual inverse, only examples of non-invertible matrices are considered below.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] It is also possible to define a pseudoinverse for scalars and vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] This amounts to treating these as matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The pseudoinverse of the null (all zero) vector is the transposed null vector.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The pseudoinverse of a squared diagonal matrix is obtained by taking the reciprocal of the nonzero diagonal elements.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] If the rank of ⁠ A ⁠ is identical to the number of columns, ⁠ n ⁠, (for ⁠ $n\leq m$ ⁠,) there are ⁠ n ⁠ linearly independent columns, and ⁠ $A^{*}A$ ⁠ is invertible.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] If the rank of ⁠ A ⁠ is identical to the number of rows, ⁠ m ⁠, (for ⁠ $m\leq n$ ⁠,) there are ⁠ m ⁠ linearly independent rows, and ⁠ $AA^{*}$ ⁠ is invertible.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] This is a special case of either full column rank or full row rank (treated above).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] If ⁠ A ⁠ is normal, that is, it commutes with its conjugate transpose, then its pseudoinverse can be computed by diagonalizing it, mapping all nonzero eigenvalues to their inverses, and mapping zero eigenvalues to zero.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] A corollary is that ⁠ A ⁠ commuting with its transpose implies that it commutes with its pseudoinverse.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] A (square) matrix ⁠ A ⁠ is said to be an EP matrix if it commutes with its pseudoinverse.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In such cases (and only in such cases), it is possible to obtain the pseudoinverse as a polynomial in ⁠ A ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] A polynomial $p(t)$ such that $A^{+}=p(A)$ can be easily obtained from the characteristic polynomial of ⁠ A ⁠ or, more generally, from any annihilating polynomial of ⁠ A ⁠.
