[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] For a circulant matrix ⁠ C ⁠, the singular value decomposition is given by the Fourier transform, that is, the singular values are the Fourier coefficients.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Let ⁠ $r\leq \min(m,n)$ ⁠ denote the rank of ⁠ $A\in \mathbb {K} ^{m\times n}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Then ⁠ A ⁠ can be (rank) decomposed as $A=BC$ where ⁠ $B\in \mathbb {K} ^{m\times r}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $C\in \mathbb {K} ^{r\times n}$ ⁠ are of rank ⁠ r ⁠.
