[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] If solutions exist but ⁠ A ⁠ does not have full column rank, then we have an indeterminate system, all of whose infinitude of solutions are given by this last equation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] For linear systems $Ax=b,$ with non-unique solutions (such as under-determined systems), the pseudoinverse may be used to construct the solution of minimum Euclidean norm $\|x\|_{2}$ among all solutions.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] A large condition number implies that the problem of finding least-squares solutions to the corresponding system of linear equations is ill-conditioned in the sense that small errors in the entries of ⁠ A ⁠ can lead to huge errors in the entries of the solution.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] It is possible to compute the Moore–Penrose inverse in a fast way with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms in the time $O({n^{\omega }})$ for $~2.37\leq \omega <3$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The weighted pseudoinverse generalizes the Moore-Penrose inverse between metric spaces with weight matrices in the domain and range.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] These weights are the identity for the standard Moore-Penrose inverse, which assumes an orthonormal basis in both spaces.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In order to solve more general least-squares problems, one can define Moore–Penrose inverses for all continuous linear operators ⁠ $A:H_{1}\rightarrow H_{2}$ ⁠ between two Hilbert spaces ⁠ $H_{1}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $H_{2}$ ⁠, using the same four conditions as in our definition above.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] It turns out that not every continuous linear operator has a continuous linear pseudoinverse in this sense.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Those that do are precisely the ones whose range is closed in ⁠ $H_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] A notion of pseudoinverse exists for matrices over an arbitrary field equipped with an arbitrary involutive automorphism.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In this more general setting, a given matrix doesn't always have a pseudoinverse.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] The necessary and sufficient condition for a pseudoinverse to exist is that $\operatorname {rank} (A)=\operatorname {rank} \left(A^{*}A\right)=\operatorname {rank} \left(AA^{*}\right)$ , where $A^{*}$ denotes the result of applying the involution operation to the transpose of A .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] **Example**: Consider the field of complex numbers equipped with the identity involution (as opposed to the involution considered elsewhere in the article); do there exist matrices that fail to have pseudoinverses in this sense?
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Consider the matrix $A={\begin{bmatrix}1&i\end{bmatrix}}^{\mathsf {T}}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] Observe that $\operatorname {rank} \left(AA^{\mathsf {T}}\right)=1$ while $\operatorname {rank} \left(A^{\mathsf {T}}A\right)=0$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] So this matrix doesn't have a pseudoinverse in this sense.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] In abstract algebra, a Moore–Penrose inverse may be defined on a *-regular semigroup.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/moore-penrose-inverse] This abstract definition coincides with the one in linear algebra.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] If a real $n\times n$ matrix A is interpreted as a linear transformation of n -dimensional space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , the polar decomposition separates it into a rotation or reflection U of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and a scaling of the space along a set of n orthogonal axes.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The polar decomposition of a square matrix A always exists.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] If A is invertible, the decomposition is unique, and the factor P will be positive-definite.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] In that case, A can be written uniquely in the form $A=Ue^{X}$ , where U is unitary, and X is the unique self-adjoint logarithm of the matrix P .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] This decomposition is useful in computing the fundamental group of (matrix) Lie groups.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The polar decomposition can also be defined as $A=P'U$ , where $P'=UPU^{-1}$ is a symmetric positive-definite matrix with the same eigenvalues as P but different eigenvectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The polar decomposition of a matrix can be seen as the matrix analog of the polar form of a complex number z as $z=ur$ , where r is its absolute value (a non-negative real number), and u is a complex number with unit norm (an element of the circle group).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The definition $A=UP$ may be extended to rectangular matrices $A\in \mathbb {C} ^{m\times n}$ by requiring $U\in \mathbb {C} ^{m\times n}$ to be a semi-unitary matrix, and $P\in \mathbb {C} ^{n\times n}$ to be a positive-semidefinite Hermitian matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The decomposition always exists, and P is always unique.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The matrix U is unique if and only if A has full rank.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] A real square $m\times m$ matrix A can be interpreted as the linear transformation of $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ that takes a column vector x to $Ax$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Then, in the polar decomposition $A=RP$ , the factor R is an $m\times m$ real orthogonal matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The polar decomposition then can be seen as expressing the linear transformation defined by A into a scaling of the space $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ along each eigenvector $e_{i}$ of P by a scale factor $\sigma _{i}$ (the action of P ), followed by a rotation of $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ (the action of R ).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Alternatively, the decomposition $A=PR$ expresses the transformation defined by A as a rotation ( R ) followed by a scaling ( P ) along certain orthogonal directions.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The scale factors are the same, but the directions are different.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The positive-semidefinite matrix *P* is always unique, even if *A* is singular, and can be obtained as $P=(A^{*}A)^{1/2},$ where $A^{*}$ denotes the conjugate transpose of A .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Here $A^{*}A$ is a positive-semidefinite Hermitian matrix and, therefore, has a unique positive-semidefinite Hermitian square root.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] In terms of the singular value decomposition (SVD) of A , $A=W\Sigma V^{*}$ , one has ${\begin{aligned}P&=V\Sigma V^{*},\\U&=WV^{*},\end{aligned}}$ where U , V , and W are unitary matrices (orthogonal if the field is the reals $\mathbb {R}$ ).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] This confirms that P is positive-definite, and U is unitary.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Thus, the existence of the SVD is equivalent to the existence of polar decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] One can also decompose A in the form $A=P'U.$ Here U is the same as before, and $P'$ is given by $P'=UPU^{-1}=(AA^{*})^{1/2}=W\Sigma W^{*}.$ This is known as the left polar decomposition, whereas the previous decomposition is known as the right polar decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Left polar decomposition is also known as reverse polar decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The **polar decomposition** of a square invertible real matrix A is of the form $A=[A]R,$ where $[A]\equiv \left(AA^{\mathsf {T}}\right)^{1/2}$ is a positive-definite matrix, and $R=[A]^{-1}A$ is an orthogonal matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The matrix A with polar decomposition $A=UP$ is normal if and only if U and P commute ( $UP=PU$ ), or equivalently, they are simultaneously diagonalizable.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The core idea behind the construction of the polar decomposition is similar to that used to compute the singular-value decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The polar decomposition is thus $A=UP,$ with U and P diagonal in the eigenbasis of A and having eigenvalues equal to the phases and absolute values of those of $A,$ respectively.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] From the singular-value decomposition, it can be shown that a matrix A is invertible if and only if $A^{*}A$ (equivalently, $AA^{*}$ ) is.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Moreover, this is true if and only if the eigenvalues of $A^{*}A$ are all not zero.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] In this case, the polar decomposition is directly obtained by writing $A=A\left(A^{*}A\right)^{-1/2}\left(A^{*}A\right)^{1/2},$ and observing that $A\left(A^{*}A\right)^{-1/2}$ is unitary.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] In this expression, $V^{*}$ is unitary because V is.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Note how, from the above construction, it follows that *the unitary matrix in the polar decomposition of an invertible matrix is uniquely defined*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The SVD of a square matrix A reads $A=WD^{1/2}V^{*}$ , with $W,V$ unitary matrices, and D a diagonal, positive semi-definite matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] We can now apply the same reasoning used in the above equation to write $A=PU=UP'$ , but now $U\equiv WV^{*}$ is not in general unitary.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Nonetheless, U has the same support and range as A , and it satisfies $U^{*}U=VV^{*}$ and $UU^{*}=WW^{*}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] This makes U into an isometry when its action is restricted onto the support of A , that is, it means that U is a partial isometry.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The **polar decomposition** of any bounded linear operator *A* between complex Hilbert spaces is a canonical factorization as the product of a partial isometry and a non-negative operator.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The operator *U* must be weakened to a partial isometry, rather than unitary, because of the following issues.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] So if *A* = *U* |*A*|, *U* must be *A*, which is not unitary.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The operator *C* can be defined by *C*(*Bh*) := *Ah* for all *h* in *H*, extended by continuity to the closure of *Ran*(*B*), and by zero on the orthogonal complement to all of *H*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The lemma then follows since *A*A* ≤ *B*B* implies ker(*B*) ⊂ ker(*A*).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] If *A*A* = *B*B*, then *C* is a partial isometry, which is unique if ker(*B**) ⊂ ker(*C*).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] In general, for any bounded operator *A*, $A^{*}A=\left(A^{*}A\right)^{1/2}\left(A^{*}A\right)^{1/2},$ where (*A*A*)1/2 is the unique positive square root of *A*A* given by the usual functional calculus.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] So by the lemma, we have $A=U\left(A^{*}A\right)^{1/2}$ for some partial isometry *U*, which is unique if ker(*A**) ⊂ ker(*U*).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Take *P* to be (*A*A*)1/2 and one obtains the polar decomposition *A* = *UP*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Notice that an analogous argument can be used to show *A = P'U'*, where *P'* is positive and *U'* a partial isometry.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] When *H* is finite-dimensional, *U* can be extended to a unitary operator; this is not true in general (see example above).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Alternatively, the polar decomposition can be shown using the operator version of singular value decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] By property of the continuous functional calculus, |*A*| is in the C*-algebra generated by *A*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] A similar but weaker statement holds for the partial isometry: *U* is in the von Neumann algebra generated by *A*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] If *A* is invertible, the polar part *U* will be in the C*-algebra as well.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The proof uses the same lemma as above, which goes through for unbounded operators in general.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The operator *A* being closed and densely defined ensures that the operator *A***A* is self-adjoint (with dense domain) and therefore allows one to define (*A***A*)1/2.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Applying the lemma gives polar decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] If an unbounded operator *A* is affiliated to a von Neumann algebra **M**, and *A* = *UP* is its polar decomposition, then *U* is in **M** and so is the spectral projection of *P*, 1*B*(*P*), for any Borel set *B* in [0, ∞).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Given any ${\hat {r}}$ on this sphere and an angle −π < *a* ≤ π, the versor $e^{a{\hat {r}}}=\cos a+{\hat {r}}\sin a$ is on the unit 3-sphere of $\mathbb {H} .$ For *a* = 0 and *a* = π, the versor is 1 or −1, regardless of which r is selected.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The norm t of a quaternion q is the Euclidean distance from the origin to q.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] When a quaternion is not just a real number, then there is a *unique* polar decomposition: $q=t\exp(a{\hat {r}}).$ Here r, a, t are all uniquely determined such that r is a right versor (*r*2 = –1), a satisfies 0 < *a* < π, and *t* > 0.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] Polar decomposition of an element of the algebra M(2, R) of 2 × 2 real matrices uses these alternative planar decompositions since any planar subalgebra is isomorphic to dual numbers, split-complex numbers, or ordinary complex numbers.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] To compute an approximation of the polar decomposition *A* = *UP*, usually the unitary factor *U* is approximated.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/polar-decomposition] The combination of inversion and Hermite conjugation is chosen so that in the singular value decomposition, the unitary factors remain the same and the iteration reduces to Heron's method on the singular values.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The data are linearly transformed onto a new coordinate system such that the directions (principal components) capturing the largest variation in the data can be easily identified.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The **principal components** of a collection of points in a real coordinate space are a sequence of p unit vectors, where the i -th vector is the direction of a line that best fits the data while being orthogonal to the first $i-1$ vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Here, a best-fitting line is defined as one that minimizes the average squared perpendicular distance from the points to the line.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] These directions (i.e., principal components) constitute an orthonormal basis in which different individual dimensions of the data are linearly uncorrelated.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Many studies use the first two principal components in order to plot the data in two dimensions and to visually identify clusters of closely related data points.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Principal component analysis has applications in many fields such as population genetics, microbiome studies, and atmospheric science.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] When performing PCA, the first principal component of a set of p variables is the derived variable formed as a linear combination of the original variables that explains the most variance.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The second principal component explains the most variance in what is left once the effect of the first component is removed, and we may proceed through p iterations until all the variance is explained.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is most commonly used when many of the variables are highly correlated with each other and it is desirable to reduce their number to an independent set.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The first principal component can equivalently be defined as a direction that maximizes the variance of the projected data.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The i -th principal component can be taken as a direction orthogonal to the first $i-1$ principal components that maximizes the variance of the projected data.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] For either objective, it can be shown that the principal components are eigenvectors of the data's covariance matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Thus, the principal components are often computed by eigendecomposition of the data covariance matrix or singular value decomposition of the data matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is the simplest of the true eigenvector-based multivariate analyses and is closely related to factor analysis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Factor analysis typically incorporates more domain-specific assumptions about the underlying structure and solves eigenvectors of a slightly different matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is also related to canonical correlation analysis (CCA).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] CCA defines coordinate systems that optimally describe the cross-covariance between two datasets while PCA defines a new orthogonal coordinate system that optimally describes variance in a single dataset.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Robust and L1-norm-based variants of standard PCA have also been proposed.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA was invented in 1901 by Karl Pearson, as an analogue of the principal axis theorem in mechanics; it was later independently developed and named by Harold Hotelling in the 1930s.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA can be thought of as fitting a *p*-dimensional ellipsoid to the data, where each axis of the ellipsoid represents a principal component.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] If some axis of the ellipsoid is small, then the variance along that axis is also small.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] To find the axes of the ellipsoid, we must first center the values of each variable in the dataset on 0 by subtracting the mean of the variable's observed values from each of those values.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] These transformed values are used instead of the original observed values for each of the variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Then, we compute the covariance matrix of the data and calculate the eigenvalues and corresponding eigenvectors of this covariance matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Then we must normalize each of the orthogonal eigenvectors to turn them into unit vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Once this is done, each of the mutually-orthogonal unit eigenvectors can be interpreted as an axis of the ellipsoid fitted to the data.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This choice of basis will transform the covariance matrix into a diagonalized form, in which the diagonal elements represent the variance of each axis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The proportion of the variance that each eigenvector represents can be calculated by dividing the eigenvalue corresponding to that eigenvector by the sum of all eigenvalues.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Biplots and scree plots (degree of explained variance) are used to interpret findings of the PCA.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] in such a way that the individual variables $t_{1},\dots ,t_{l}$ of **t** considered over the data set successively inherit the maximum possible variance from **X**, with each coefficient vector **w** constrained to be a unit vector.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The quantity to be maximised can be recognised as a Rayleigh quotient.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] A standard result for a positive semidefinite matrix such as **X**T**X** is that the quotient's maximum possible value is the largest eigenvalue of the matrix, which occurs when ***w*** is the corresponding eigenvector.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] With **w**(1) found, the first principal component of a data vector **x**(*i*) can then be given as a score *t*1(*i*) = **x**(*i*) ⋅ **w**(1) in the transformed co-ordinates, or as the corresponding vector in the original variables, {**x**(*i*) ⋅ **w**(1)} **w**(1).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] It turns out that this gives the remaining eigenvectors of **X**T**X**, with the maximum values for the quantity in brackets given by their corresponding eigenvalues.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Thus the weight vectors are eigenvectors of **X**T**X**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] where **W** is a *p*-by-*p* matrix of weights whose columns are the eigenvectors of **X**T**X**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The transpose of **W** is sometimes called the whitening or sphering transformation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Columns of **W** multiplied by the square root of corresponding eigenvalues, that is, eigenvectors scaled up by the variances, are called *loadings* in PCA or in Factor analysis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] where the eigenvalue property of **w**(*k*) has been used to move from line 2 to line 3.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] However eigenvectors **w**(*j*) and **w**(*k*) corresponding to eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix are orthogonal (if the eigenvalues are different), or can be orthogonalised (if the vectors happen to share an equal repeated value).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The product in the final line is therefore zero; there is no sample covariance between different principal components over the dataset.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Another way to characterise the principal components transformation is therefore as the transformation to coordinates which diagonalise the empirical sample covariance matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] where **Λ** is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues *λ*(*k*) of **X**T**X**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The transformation **P** = **X** **W** maps a data vector **x**(*i*) from an original space of *x* variables to a new space of *p* variables which are uncorrelated over the dataset.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] These norms are used to transform the original space of variables *x, y* to a new space of uncorrelated variables *p, q* (given *Yc* with same meaning), such that $p_{i}={\frac {X_{i}}{X_{c}}},\quad q_{i}={\frac {Y_{i}}{Y_{c}}}$ ; and the new variables are linearly related as: $q=\alpha p$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Such dimensionality reduction can be a very useful step for visualising and processing high-dimensional datasets, while still retaining as much of the variance in the dataset as possible.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Similarly, in regression analysis, the larger the number of explanatory variables allowed, the greater is the chance of overfitting the model, producing conclusions that fail to generalise to other datasets.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] One approach, especially when there are strong correlations between different possible explanatory variables, is to reduce them to a few principal components and then run the regression against them, a method called principal component regression.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Dimensionality reduction may also be appropriate when the variables in a dataset are noisy.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] However, with more of the total variance concentrated in the first few principal components compared to the same noise variance, the proportionate effect of the noise is less—the first few components achieve a higher signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA thus can have the effect of concentrating much of the signal into the first few principal components, which can usefully be captured by dimensionality reduction; while the later principal components may be dominated by noise, and so disposed of without great loss.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] If the dataset is not too large, the significance of the principal components can be tested using parametric bootstrap, as an aid in determining how many principal components to retain.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] where **$\mathbf {\hat {\Sigma }}$** is the square diagonal matrix with the singular values of **X**and the excess zeros chopped off that satisfies**$\mathbf {{\hat {\Sigma }}^{2}} =\mathbf {\Sigma } ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {\Sigma }$**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Comparison with the eigenvector factorization of **X**T**X** establishes that the right singular vectors **W** of **X** are equivalent to the eigenvectors of **X**T**X**, while the singular values *σ*(*k*) of **$\mathbf {X}$** are equal to the square-root of the eigenvalues *λ*(*k*) of **X**T**X**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] so each column of **T** is given by one of the left singular vectors of **X** multiplied by the corresponding singular value.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This form is also the polar decomposition of **T**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Efficient algorithms exist to calculate the SVD of **X** without having to form the matrix **X**T**X**, so computing the SVD is now the standard way to calculate a principal components analysis from a data matrix, unless only a handful of components are required.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The singular values (in **Σ**) are the square roots of the eigenvalues of the matrix **X**T**X**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Each eigenvalue is proportional to the portion of the "variance" (more correctly of the sum of the squared distances of the points from their multidimensional mean) that is associated with each eigenvector.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The sum of all the eigenvalues is equal to the sum of the squared distances of the points from their multidimensional mean.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA essentially rotates the set of points around their mean in order to align with the principal components.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This moves as much of the variance as possible (using an orthogonal transformation) into the first few dimensions.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The values in the remaining dimensions, therefore, tend to be small and may be dropped with minimal loss of information (see below).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is often used in this manner for dimensionality reduction.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA has the distinction of being the optimal orthogonal transformation for keeping the subspace that has largest "variance" (as defined above).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This advantage, however, comes at the price of greater computational requirements if compared, for example, and when applicable, to the discrete cosine transform, and in particular to the DCT-II which is simply known as the "DCT".
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques tend to be more computationally demanding than PCA.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is sensitive to the scaling of the variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Mathematically this sensitivity comes from the way a rescaling changes the sample‑covariance matrix that PCA diagonalises.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Because the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of $\Sigma ^{(\alpha )}$ are those of $\Sigma$ scaled by D , the principal axes rotate toward any column whose variance has been inflated, exactly as the 2‑D example below illustrates.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] If we have just two variables and they have the same sample variance and are completely correlated, then the PCA will entail a rotation by 45° and the "weights" (they are the cosines of rotation) for the two variables with respect to the principal component will be equal.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] But if we multiply all values of the first variable by 100, then the first principal component will be almost the same as that variable, with a small contribution from the other variable, whereas the second component will be almost aligned with the second original variable.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This means that whenever the different variables have different units (like temperature and mass), PCA is a somewhat arbitrary method of analysis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] (Different results would be obtained if one used Fahrenheit rather than Celsius for example.) Pearson's original paper was entitled "On Lines and Planes of Closest Fit to Systems of Points in Space" – "in space" implies physical Euclidean space where such concerns do not arise.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] One way of making the PCA less arbitrary is to use variables scaled so as to have unit variance, by standardizing the data and hence use the autocorrelation matrix instead of the autocovariance matrix as a basis for PCA.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] However, this compresses (or expands) the fluctuations in all dimensions of the signal space to unit variance.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Classical PCA assumes the cloud of points has already been translated so its centroid is at the origin.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] where $\mathbf {Z}$ is the centered matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The rank‑one term $n\,{\boldsymbol {\mu }}{\boldsymbol {\mu }}^{\mathsf {T}}$ often dominates, forcing the leading eigenvector to point almost exactly toward the mean and obliterating any structure in the centred part $\mathbf {Z}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] After mean subtraction that term vanishes and the principal axes align with the true directions of maximal variance.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Mean-centering is unnecessary if performing a principal components analysis on a correlation matrix, as the data are already centered after calculating correlations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Correlations are derived from the cross-product of two standard scores (Z-scores) or statistical moments (hence the name: *Pearson Product-Moment Correlation*).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Also see the article by Kromrey & Foster-Johnson (1998) on *"Mean-centering in Moderated Regression: Much Ado About Nothing"*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Since covariances are correlations of normalized variables (Z- or standard-scores) a PCA based on the correlation matrix of **X** is equal to a PCA based on the covariance matrix of **Z**, the standardized version of **X**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is a popular primary technique in pattern recognition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] It is not, however, optimized for class separability.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] However, it has been used to quantify the distance between two or more classes by calculating center of mass for each class in principal component space and reporting Euclidean distance between center of mass of two or more classes.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The linear discriminant analysis is an alternative which is optimized for class separability.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The statistical implication of this property is that the last few PCs are not simply unstructured left-overs after removing the important PCs.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Because these last PCs have variances as small as possible they are useful in their own right.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] They can help to detect unsuspected near-constant linear relationships between the elements of x, and they may also be useful in regression, in selecting a subset of variables from x, and in outlier detection.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] As noted above, the results of PCA depend on the scaling of the variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This can be cured by scaling each feature by its standard deviation, so that one ends up with dimensionless features with unital variance.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The applicability of PCA as described above is limited by certain (tacit) assumptions made in its derivation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] In particular, PCA can capture linear correlations between the features but fails when this assumption is violated (see Figure 6a in the reference).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] In some cases, coordinate transformations can restore the linearity assumption and PCA can then be applied (see kernel PCA).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Another limitation is the mean-removal process before constructing the covariance matrix for PCA.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] In fields such as astronomy, all the signals are non-negative, and the mean-removal process will force the mean of some astrophysical exposures to be zero, which consequently creates unphysical negative fluxes, and forward modeling has to be performed to recover the true magnitude of the signals.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] As an alternative method, non-negative matrix factorization focusing only on the non-negative elements in the matrices is well-suited for astrophysical observations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] See more at the relation between PCA and non-negative matrix factorization.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is at a disadvantage if the data has not been standardized before applying the algorithm to it.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA transforms the original data into data that is relevant to the principal components of that data, which means that the new data variables cannot be interpreted in the same ways that the originals were.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] They are linear interpretations of the original variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Also, if PCA is not performed properly, there is a high likelihood of information loss.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] If a dataset has a pattern hidden inside it that is nonlinear, then PCA can actually steer the analysis in the complete opposite direction of progress.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Researchers at Kansas State University discovered that the sampling error in their experiments impacted the bias of PCA results.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] "If the number of subjects or blocks is smaller than 30, and/or the researcher is interested in PC's beyond the first, it may be better to first correct for the serial correlation, before PCA is conducted".
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The researchers at Kansas State also found that PCA could be "seriously biased if the autocorrelation structure of the data are not correctly handled".
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Dimensionality reduction results in a loss of information, in general.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA-based dimensionality reduction tends to minimize that information loss, under certain signal and noise models.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] that is, that the data vector $\mathbf {x}$ is the sum of the desired information-bearing signal $\mathbf {s}$ and a noise signal $\mathbf {n}$ one can show that PCA can be optimal for dimensionality reduction, from an information-theoretic point-of-view.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The optimality of PCA is also preserved if the noise $\mathbf {n}$ is iid and at least more Gaussian (in terms of the Kullback–Leibler divergence) than the information-bearing signal $\mathbf {s}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] In general, even if the above signal model holds, PCA loses its information-theoretic optimality as soon as the noise $\mathbf {n}$ becomes dependent.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The following is a detailed description of PCA using the covariance method as opposed to the correlation method.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The goal is to transform a given data set **X** of dimension *p* to an alternative data set **Y** of smaller dimension *L*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] **Calculate the deviations from the mean** Mean subtraction is an integral part of the solution towards finding a principal component basis that minimizes the mean square error of approximating the data.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Hence we proceed by centering the data as follows: In some applications, each variable (column of **B**) may also be scaled to have a variance equal to 1 (see Z-score).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This step affects the calculated principal components, but makes them independent of the units used to measure the different variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] **Project the data onto the new basis** That is, the first column of $\mathbf {T}$ is the projection of the data points onto the first principal component, the second column is the projection onto the second principal component, etc.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Let **X** be a *d*-dimensional random vector expressed as column vector.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Without loss of generality, assume **X** has zero mean.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] We want to find $(\ast )$ a *d* × *d* orthonormal transformation matrix **P** so that **PX** has a diagonal covariance matrix (that is, **PX** is a random vector with all its distinct components pairwise uncorrelated).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Hence $(\ast )$ holds if and only if $\operatorname {cov} (X)$ were diagonalisable by P .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This is very constructive, as cov(**X**) is guaranteed to be a non-negative definite matrix and thus is guaranteed to be diagonalisable by some unitary matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] In practical implementations, especially with high dimensional data (large p), the naive covariance method is rarely used because it is not efficient due to high computational and memory costs of explicitly determining the covariance matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The covariance-free approach avoids the *np*2 operations of explicitly calculating and storing the covariance matrix **XTX**, instead utilizing one of matrix-free methods, for example, based on the function evaluating the product **XT(X r)** at the cost of 2*np* operations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] One way to compute the first principal component efficiently is shown in the following pseudo-code, for a data matrix **X** with zero mean, without ever computing its covariance matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This power iteration algorithm simply calculates the vector **XT(X r)**, normalizes, and places the result back in **r**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The eigenvalue is approximated by **rT (XTX) r**, which is the Rayleigh quotient on the unit vector **r** for the covariance matrix **XTX**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] If the largest singular value is well separated from the next largest one, the vector **r** gets close to the first principal component of **X** within the number of iterations c, which is small relative to p, at the total cost *2cnp*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The power iteration convergence can be accelerated without noticeably sacrificing the small cost per iteration using more advanced matrix-free methods, such as the Lanczos algorithm or the Locally Optimal Block Preconditioned Conjugate Gradient (LOBPCG) method.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Subsequent principal components can be computed one-by-one via deflation or simultaneously as a block.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] In the former approach, imprecisions in already computed approximate principal components additively affect the accuracy of the subsequently computed principal components, thus increasing the error with every new computation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The latter approach in the block power method replaces single-vectors **r** and **s** with block-vectors, matrices **R** and **S**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Every column of **R** approximates one of the leading principal components, while all columns are iterated simultaneously.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The main calculation is evaluation of the product **XT(X R)**.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Implemented, for example, in LOBPCG, efficient blocking eliminates the accumulation of the errors, allows using high-level BLAS matrix-matrix product functions, and typically leads to faster convergence, compared to the single-vector one-by-one technique.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The matrix deflation by subtraction is performed by subtracting the outer product, **t**1**r**1T from **X** leaving the deflated residual matrix used to calculate the subsequent leading PCs.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] For large data matrices, or matrices that have a high degree of column collinearity, NIPALS suffers from loss of orthogonality of PCs due to machine precision round-off errors accumulated in each iteration and matrix deflation by subtraction.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] A Gram–Schmidt re-orthogonalization algorithm is applied to both the scores and the loadings at each iteration step to eliminate this loss of orthogonality.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] In an "online" or "streaming" situation with data arriving piece by piece rather than being stored in a single batch, it is useful to make an estimate of the PCA projection that can be updated sequentially.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] This can be done efficiently, but requires different algorithms.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] In exploratory data analysis, qualitative (categorical) variables not used to construct the model can be projected onto the principal component axes as supplementary elements.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] The use of supplementary qualitative variables was a defining feature of the French school of data analysis developed in the 1960s and 70s.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p01] Based upon the work of Ludovic Lebart, the method is available in the R environment through packages such as FactoMineR.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The earliest application of factor analysis was in locating and measuring components of human intelligence.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The pioneering statistical psychologist Spearman actually developed factor analysis in 1904 for his two-factor theory of intelligence, adding a formal technique to the science of psychometrics.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 1924 Thurstone looked for 56 factors of intelligence, developing the notion of Mental Age.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Standard IQ tests today are based on this early work.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 1949, Shevky and Williams introduced the theory of **factorial ecology**, which dominated studies of residential differentiation from the 1950s to the 1970s.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Neighbourhoods in a city were recognizable or could be distinguished from one another by various characteristics which could be reduced to three by factor analysis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] These were known as 'social rank' (an index of occupational status), 'familism' or family size, and 'ethnicity'; Cluster analysis could then be applied to divide the city into clusters or precincts according to values of the three key factor variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] An extensive literature developed around factorial ecology in urban geography, but the approach went out of fashion after 1980 as being methodologically primitive and having little place in postmodern geographical paradigms.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] One of the problems with factor analysis has always been finding convincing names for the various artificial factors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 2000, Flood revived the factorial ecology approach to show that principal components analysis actually gave meaningful answers directly, without resorting to factor rotation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The principal components were actually dual variables or shadow prices of 'forces' pushing people together or apart in cities.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The first component was 'accessibility', the classic trade-off between demand for travel and demand for space, around which classical urban economics is based.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The next two components were 'disadvantage', which keeps people of similar status in separate neighbourhoods (mediated by planning), and ethnicity, where people of similar ethnic backgrounds try to co-locate.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] About the same time, the Australian Bureau of Statistics defined distinct indexes of advantage and disadvantage taking the first principal component of sets of key variables that were thought to be important.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] These SEIFA indexes are regularly published for various jurisdictions, and are used frequently in spatial analysis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA can be used as a formal method for the development of indexes.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] As an alternative confirmatory composite analysis has been proposed to develop and assess indexes.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The City Development Index was developed by PCA from about 200 indicators of city outcomes in a 1996 survey of 254 global cities.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The first principal component was subject to iterative regression, adding the original variables singly until about 90% of its variation was accounted for.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The index ultimately used about 15 indicators but was a good predictor of many more variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Its comparative value agreed very well with a subjective assessment of the condition of each city.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The coefficients on items of infrastructure were roughly proportional to the average costs of providing the underlying services, suggesting the Index was actually a measure of effective physical and social investment in the city.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The country-level Human Development Index (HDI) from UNDP, which has been published since 1990 and is very extensively used in development studies, has very similar coefficients on similar indicators, strongly suggesting it was originally constructed using PCA.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 1978 Cavalli-Sforza and others pioneered the use of principal components analysis (PCA) to summarise data on variation in human gene frequencies across regions.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The components showed distinctive patterns, including gradients and sinusoidal waves.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] They interpreted these patterns as resulting from specific ancient migration events.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Since then, PCA has been ubiquitous in population genetics, with thousands of papers using PCA as a display mechanism.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Genetics varies largely according to proximity, so the first two principal components actually show spatial distribution and may be used to map the relative geographical location of different population groups, thereby showing individuals who have wandered from their original locations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA in genetics has been technically controversial, in that the technique has been performed on discrete non-normal variables and often on binary allele markers.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The lack of any measures of standard error in PCA are also an impediment to more consistent usage.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In August 2022, the molecular biologist Eran Elhaik published a theoretical paper in Scientific Reports analyzing 12 PCA applications.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] He concluded that it was easy to manipulate the method, which, in his view, generated results that were 'erroneous, contradictory, and absurd.' Specifically, he argued, the results achieved in population genetics were characterized by cherry-picking and circular reasoning.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Market research has been an extensive user of PCA.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is used to develop customer satisfaction or customer loyalty scores for products, and with clustering, to develop market segments that may be targeted with advertising campaigns, in much the same way as factorial ecology will locate geographical areas with similar characteristics.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA rapidly transforms large amounts of data into smaller, easier-to-digest variables that can be more rapidly and readily analyzed.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In any consumer questionnaire, there are series of questions designed to elicit consumer attitudes, and principal components seek out latent variables underlying these attitudes.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] For example, the Oxford Internet Survey in 2013 asked 2000 people about their attitudes and beliefs, and from these analysts extracted four principal component dimensions, which they identified as 'escape', 'social networking', 'efficiency', and 'problem creating'.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Another example from Joe Flood in 2008 extracted an attitudinal index toward housing from 28 attitude questions in a national survey of 2697 households in Australia.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The first principal component represented a general attitude toward property and home ownership.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The index, or the attitude questions it embodied, could be fed into a General Linear Model of tenure choice.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The strongest determinant of private renting by far was the attitude index, rather than income, marital status or household type.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In quantitative finance, PCA is used in financial risk management, and has been applied to other problems such as portfolio optimization.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is commonly used in problems involving fixed income securities and portfolios, and interest rate derivatives.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Valuations here depend on the entire yield curve, comprising numerous highly correlated instruments, and PCA is used to define a set of components or factors that explain rate movements, thereby facilitating the modelling.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] One common risk management application is to calculating value at risk, VaR, applying PCA to the Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Here, for each simulation-sample, the components are stressed, and rates, and in turn option values, are then reconstructed; with VaR calculated, finally, over the entire run.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is also used in hedging exposure to interest rate risk, given partial durations and other sensitivities.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Under both, the first three, typically, principal components of the system are of interest (representing "shift", "twist", and "curvature").
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] These principal components are derived from an eigen-decomposition of the covariance matrix of yield at predefined maturities; and where the variance of each component is its eigenvalue (and as the components are orthogonal, no correlation need be incorporated in subsequent modelling).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] For equity, an optimal portfolio is one where the expected return is maximized for a given level of risk, or alternatively, where risk is minimized for a given return; see Markowitz model for discussion.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Thus, one approach is to reduce portfolio risk, where allocation strategies are applied to the "principal portfolios" instead of the underlying stocks.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] A second approach is to enhance portfolio return, using the principal components to select companies' stocks with upside potential.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA has also been used to understand relationships between international equity markets, and within markets between groups of companies in industries or sectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA may also be applied to stress testing, essentially an analysis of a bank's ability to endure a hypothetical adverse economic scenario.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] A variant of principal components analysis is used in neuroscience to identify the specific properties of a stimulus that increases a neuron's probability of generating an action potential.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] This technique is known as spike-triggered covariance analysis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In a typical application an experimenter presents a white noise process as a stimulus (usually either as a sensory input to a test subject, or as a current injected directly into the neuron) and records a train of action potentials, or spikes, produced by the neuron as a result.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Presumably, certain features of the stimulus make the neuron more likely to spike.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In order to extract these features, the experimenter calculates the covariance matrix of the *spike-triggered ensemble*, the set of all stimuli (defined and discretized over a finite time window, typically on the order of 100 ms) that immediately preceded a spike.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Specifically, the eigenvectors with the largest positive eigenvalues correspond to the directions along which the variance of the spike-triggered ensemble showed the largest positive change compared to the variance of the prior.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Since these were the directions in which varying the stimulus led to a spike, they are often good approximations of the sought after relevant stimulus features.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In neuroscience, PCA is also used to discern the identity of a neuron from the shape of its action potential.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Spike sorting is an important procedure because extracellular recording techniques often pick up signals from more than one neuron.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In spike sorting, one first uses PCA to reduce the dimensionality of the space of action potential waveforms, and then performs clustering analysis to associate specific action potentials with individual neurons.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA as a dimension reduction technique is particularly suited to detect coordinated activities of large neuronal ensembles.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] It has been used in determining collective variables, that is, order parameters, during phase transitions in the brain.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Correspondence analysis (CA) was developed by Jean-Paul Benzécri and is conceptually similar to PCA, but scales the data (which should be non-negative) so that rows and columns are treated equivalently.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is traditionally applied to contingency tables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] CA decomposes the chi-squared statistic associated to this table into orthogonal factors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Because CA is a descriptive technique, it can be applied to tables for which the chi-squared statistic is appropriate or not.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Several variants of CA are available including detrended correspondence analysis and canonical correspondence analysis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] One special extension is multiple correspondence analysis, which may be seen as the counterpart of principal component analysis for categorical data.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Principal component analysis creates variables that are linear combinations of the original variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The new variables have the property that the variables are all orthogonal.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The PCA transformation can be helpful as a pre-processing step before clustering.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is a variance-focused approach seeking to reproduce the total variable variance, in which components reflect both common and unique variance of the variable.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is generally preferred for purposes of data reduction (that is, translating variable space into optimal factor space) but not when the goal is to detect the latent construct or factors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Factor analysis is similar to principal component analysis, in that factor analysis also involves linear combinations of variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Different from PCA, factor analysis is a correlation-focused approach seeking to reproduce the inter-correlations among variables, in which the factors "represent the common variance of variables, excluding unique variance".
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In terms of the correlation matrix, this corresponds with focusing on explaining the off-diagonal terms (that is, shared co-variance), while PCA focuses on explaining the terms that sit on the diagonal.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] However, as a side result, when trying to reproduce the on-diagonal terms, PCA also tends to fit relatively well the off-diagonal correlations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Results given by PCA and factor analysis are very similar in most situations, but this is not always the case, and there are some problems where the results are significantly different.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Factor analysis is generally used when the research purpose is detecting data structure (that is, latent constructs or factors) or causal modeling.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] If the factor model is incorrectly formulated or the assumptions are not met, then factor analysis will give erroneous results.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] It has been asserted that the relaxed solution of *k*-means clustering, specified by the cluster indicators, is given by the principal components, and the PCA subspace spanned by the principal directions is identical to the cluster centroid subspace.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] However, that PCA is a useful relaxation of *k*-means clustering was not a new result, and it is straightforward to uncover counterexamples to the statement that the cluster centroid subspace is spanned by the principal directions.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Non-negative matrix factorization (NMF) is a dimension reduction method where only non-negative elements in the matrices are used, which is therefore a promising method in astronomy, in the sense that astrophysical signals are non-negative.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The PCA components are orthogonal to each other, while the NMF components are all non-negative and therefore constructs a non-orthogonal basis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In PCA, the contribution of each component is ranked based on the magnitude of its corresponding eigenvalue, which is equivalent to the fractional residual variance (FRV) in analyzing empirical data.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] For NMF, its components are ranked based only on the empirical FRV curves.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The FRV curves for NMF is decreasing continuously when the NMF components are constructed sequentially, indicating the continuous capturing of quasi-static noise; then converge to higher levels than PCA, indicating the less over-fitting property of NMF.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is often difficult to interpret the principal components when the data include many variables of various origins, or when some variables are qualitative.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] This leads the PCA user to a delicate elimination of several variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] If observations or variables have an excessive impact on the direction of the axes, they should be removed and then projected as supplementary elements.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In addition, it is necessary to avoid interpreting the proximities between the points close to the center of the factorial plane.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The iconography of correlations, on the contrary, which is not a projection on a system of axes, does not have these drawbacks.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] We can therefore keep all the variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The principle of the diagram is to underline the "remarkable" correlations of the correlation matrix, by a solid line (positive correlation) or dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] A strong correlation is not "remarkable" if it is not direct, but caused by the effect of a third variable.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Conversely, weak correlations can be "remarkable".
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] For example, if a variable Y depends on several independent variables, the correlations of Y with each of them are weak and yet "remarkable".
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] A particular disadvantage of PCA is that the principal components are usually linear combinations of all input variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Sparse PCA overcomes this disadvantage by finding linear combinations that contain just a few input variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] It extends the classic method of principal component analysis (PCA) for the reduction of dimensionality of data by adding sparsity constraint on the input variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The methodological and theoretical developments of Sparse PCA as well as its applications in scientific studies were recently reviewed in a survey paper.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Most of the modern methods for nonlinear dimensionality reduction find their theoretical and algorithmic roots in PCA or K-means.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Pearson's original idea was to take a straight line (or plane) which will be "the best fit" to a set of data points.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Trevor Hastie expanded on this concept by proposing **Principal curves** as the natural extension for the geometric interpretation of PCA, which explicitly constructs a manifold for data approximation followed by projecting the points onto it.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] See also the elastic map algorithm and principal geodesic analysis.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Another popular generalization is kernel PCA, which corresponds to PCA performed in a reproducing kernel Hilbert space associated with a positive definite kernel.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] In multilinear subspace learning, PCA is generalized to multilinear PCA (MPCA) that extracts features directly from tensor representations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] MPCA is solved by performing PCA in each mode of the tensor iteratively.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] MPCA has been applied to face recognition, gait recognition, etc.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] MPCA is further extended to uncorrelated MPCA, non-negative MPCA and robust MPCA.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] While PCA finds the mathematically optimal method (as in minimizing the squared error), it is still sensitive to outliers in the data that produce large errors, something that the method tries to avoid in the first place.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is therefore common practice to remove outliers before computing PCA.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] However, in some contexts, outliers can be difficult to identify.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] For example, in data mining algorithms like correlation clustering, the assignment of points to clusters and outliers is not known beforehand.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] A recently proposed generalization of PCA based on a weighted PCA increases robustness by assigning different weights to data objects based on their estimated relevancy.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Outlier-resistant variants of PCA have also been proposed, based on L1-norm formulations (L1-PCA).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Robust principal component analysis (RPCA) via decomposition in low-rank and sparse matrices is a modification of PCA that works well with respect to grossly corrupted observations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Independent component analysis (ICA) is directed to similar problems as principal component analysis, but finds additively separable components rather than successive approximations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Given a matrix E , it tries to decompose it into two matrices such that $E=AP$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] A key difference from techniques such as PCA and ICA is that some of the entries of A are constrained to be 0.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Each column of A must have at least $L-1$ zeroes where L is the number of columns of A (or alternatively the number of rows of P ).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The justification for this criterion is that if a node is removed from the regulatory layer along with all the output nodes connected to it, the result must still be characterized by a connectivity matrix with full column rank.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] then the decomposition is unique up to multiplication by a scalar.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Discriminant analysis of principal components (DAPC) is a multivariate method used to identify and describe clusters of genetically related individuals.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Genetic variation is partitioned into two components: variation between groups and within groups, and it maximizes the former.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Linear discriminants are linear combinations of alleles which best separate the clusters.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Alleles that most contribute to this discrimination are therefore those that are the most markedly different across groups.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] A DAPC can be realized on R using the package Adegenet.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Directional component analysis (DCA) is a method used in the atmospheric sciences for analysing multivariate datasets.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Like PCA, it allows for dimension reduction, improved visualization and improved interpretability of large data-sets.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Also like PCA, it is based on a covariance matrix derived from the input dataset.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The difference between PCA and DCA is that DCA additionally requires the input of a vector direction, referred to as the impact.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] Whereas PCA maximises explained variance, DCA maximises probability density given impact.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] The motivation for DCA is to find components of a multivariate dataset that are both likely (measured using probability density) and important (measured using the impact).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/principal-component-analysis-p02] DCA has been used to find the most likely and most serious heat-wave patterns in weather prediction ensembles , and the most likely and most impactful changes in rainfall due to climate change .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] In linear algebra, the **rank** of a matrix A is the dimension of the vector space generated (or spanned) by its columns.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] This corresponds to the maximal number of linearly independent columns of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] This, in turn, is identical to the dimension of the vector space spanned by its rows.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Rank is thus a measure of the "nondegenerateness" of the system of linear equations and linear transformation encoded by A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] There are multiple equivalent definitions of rank.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] A matrix's rank is one of its most fundamental characteristics.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The rank is commonly denoted by rank(*A*) or rk(*A*); sometimes the parentheses are not written, as in rank *A*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The rank can also be denoted by rg(*A*), from German *Rang*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] More generally, the rank of a linear map between two vector spaces is the dimension of its image.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] In this section, we give some definitions of the rank of a matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Many definitions are possible; see Alternative definitions for several of these.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The **column rank** of A is the dimension of the column space of A, while the **row rank** of A is the dimension of the row space of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] A fundamental result in linear algebra is that the column rank and the row rank are always equal.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] (Three proofs of this result are given in § Proofs that column rank = row rank, below.) This number (i.e., the number of linearly independent rows or columns) is simply called the **rank** of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] A matrix is said to have **full rank** if its rank equals the largest possible for a matrix of the same dimensions, which is the lesser of the number of rows and columns.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] A matrix is said to be **rank-deficient** if it does not have full rank.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The **rank deficiency** of a matrix is the difference between the lesser of the number of rows and columns, and the rank.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of a linear map or operator $\Phi$ is defined as the dimension of its image: $\operatorname {rank} (\Phi ):=\dim(\operatorname {img} (\Phi ))$ where $\dim$ is the dimension of a vector space, and $\operatorname {img}$ is the image of a map.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The matrix $A={\begin{bmatrix}1&1&0&2\\-1&-1&0&-2\end{bmatrix}}$ has rank 1: there are nonzero columns, so the rank is positive, but any pair of columns is linearly dependent.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Indeed, since the column vectors of A are the row vectors of the transpose of A, the statement that the column rank of a matrix equals its row rank is equivalent to the statement that the rank of a matrix is equal to the rank of its transpose, i.e., rank(*A*) = rank(*A*T).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] A common approach to finding the rank of a matrix is to reduce it to a simpler form, generally row echelon form, by elementary row operations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Row operations do not change the row space (hence do not change the row rank), and, being invertible, map the column space to an isomorphic space (hence do not change the column rank).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Once in row echelon form, the rank is clearly the same for both row rank and column rank, and equals the number of pivots (or basic columns) and also the number of non-zero rows.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] When applied to floating point computations on computers, basic Gaussian elimination (LU decomposition) can be unreliable, and a rank-revealing decomposition should be used instead.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] An effective alternative is the singular value decomposition (SVD), but there are other less computationally expensive choices, such as QR decomposition with pivoting (so-called rank-revealing QR factorization), which are still more numerically robust than Gaussian elimination.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Numerical determination of rank requires a criterion for deciding when a value, such as a singular value from the SVD, should be treated as zero, a practical choice which depends on both the matrix and the application.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The fact that the column and row ranks of any matrix are equal is fundamental in linear algebra.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] One of the most elementary ones has been sketched in § Rank from row echelon forms.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] It is straightforward to show that neither the row rank nor the column rank are changed by an elementary row operation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] As Gaussian elimination proceeds by elementary row operations, the reduced row echelon form of a matrix has the same row rank and the same column rank as the original matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Further elementary column operations allow putting the matrix in the form of an identity matrix possibly bordered by rows and columns of zeros.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Again, this changes neither the row rank nor the column rank.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] It is immediate that both the row and column ranks of this resulting matrix is the number of its nonzero entries.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] We present two other proofs of this result.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The first uses only basic properties of linear combinations of vectors, and is valid over any field.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The second uses orthogonality and is valid for matrices over the real numbers; it is based upon Mackiw (1995).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Both proofs can be found in the book by Banerjee and Roy (2014).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Let the column rank of A be r, and let **c**1, ..., **c***r* be any basis for the column space of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Place these as the columns of an *m* × *r* matrix C.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Every column of A can be expressed as a linear combination of the r columns in C.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] This means that there is an *r* × *n* matrix R such that *A* = *CR*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] R is the matrix whose ith column is formed from the coefficients giving the ith column of A as a linear combination of the r columns of C.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] In other words, R is the matrix which contains the multiples for the bases of the column space of A (which is C), which are then used to form A as a whole.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Now, each row of A is given by a linear combination of the r rows of R.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Therefore, the rows of R form a spanning set of the row space of A and, by the Steinitz exchange lemma, the row rank of A cannot exceed r.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] This proves that the row rank of A is less than or equal to the column rank of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] This result can be applied to any matrix, so apply the result to the transpose of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Since the row rank of the transpose of A is the column rank of A and the column rank of the transpose of A is the row rank of A, this establishes the reverse inequality and we obtain the equality of the row rank and the column rank of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Let A be an *m* × *n* matrix with entries in the real numbers whose row rank is r.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Therefore, the dimension of the row space of A is r.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] We make two observations: (a) **v** is a linear combination of vectors in the row space of A, which implies that **v** belongs to the row space of A, and (b) since *A***v** = 0, the vector **v** is orthogonal to every row vector of A and, hence, is orthogonal to every vector in the row space of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Every *A***x***i* is in the column space of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] So, *A***x**1, *A***x**2, ..., *A***x***r* is a set of r linearly independent vectors in the column space of A and, hence, the dimension of the column space of A (i.e., the column rank of A) must be at least as big as r.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] This proves that row rank of A is no larger than the column rank of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Now apply this result to the transpose of A to get the reverse inequality and conclude as in the previous proof.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] In all the definitions in this section, the matrix A is taken to be an *m* × *n* matrix over an arbitrary field F.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Given the matrix A , there is an associated linear mapping $f:F^{n}\to F^{m}$ defined by $f(x)=Ax.$ The rank of A is the dimension of the image of f .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] This definition has the advantage that it can be applied to any linear map without need for a specific matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Given the same linear mapping f as above, the rank is n minus the dimension of the kernel of f.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The rank–nullity theorem states that this definition is equivalent to the preceding one.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A is the maximal number of linearly independent rows of A; this is the dimension of the row space of A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A is the smallest positive integer k such that A can be factored as $A=CR$ , where C is an *m* × *k* matrix and R is a *k* × *n* matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] 5. the row rank of A is less than or equal to k.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Indeed, the following equivalences are obvious: $(1)\Leftrightarrow (2)\Leftrightarrow (3)\Leftrightarrow (4)\Leftrightarrow (5)$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] For example, to prove (3) from (2), take C to be the matrix whose columns are $\mathbf {c} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {c} _{k}$ from (2).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] To prove (2) from (3), take $\mathbf {c} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {c} _{k}$ to be the columns of C.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] It follows from the equivalence $(1)\Leftrightarrow (5)$ that the row rank is equal to the column rank.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Unfortunately, this definition does not suggest an efficient manner to compute the rank (for which it is better to use one of the alternative definitions).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A equals the number of non-zero singular values, which is the same as the number of non-zero diagonal elements in Σ in the singular value decomposition $A=U\Sigma V^{*}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A is the largest order of any non-zero minor in A.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A is the smallest number k such that A can be written as a sum of k rank 1 matrices, where a matrix is defined to have rank 1 if and only if it can be written as a nonzero product $c\cdot r$ of a column vector c and a row vector r.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] This notion of rank is called tensor rank; it can be generalized in the separable models interpretation of the singular value decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] We assume that A is an *m* × *n* matrix, and we define the linear map f by *f*(**x**) = *A***x** as above.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] This is a special case of the next inequality.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] , each have only the zero vector in common.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] One useful application of calculating the rank of a matrix is the computation of the number of solutions of a system of linear equations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] According to the Rouché–Capelli theorem, the system is inconsistent if the rank of the augmented matrix is greater than the rank of the coefficient matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] If on the other hand, the ranks of these two matrices are equal, then the system must have at least one solution.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The solution is unique if and only if the rank equals the number of variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Otherwise the general solution has k free parameters where k is the difference between the number of variables and the rank.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] In this case (and assuming the system of equations is in the real or complex numbers) the system of equations has infinitely many solutions.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] In control theory, the rank of a matrix can be used to determine whether a linear system is controllable, or observable.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] In the field of communication complexity, the rank of the communication matrix of a function gives bounds on the amount of communication needed for two parties to compute the function.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] There are different generalizations of the concept of rank to matrices over arbitrary rings, where column rank, row rank, dimension of column space, and dimension of row space of a matrix may be different from the others or may not exist.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Thinking of matrices as tensors, the tensor rank generalizes to arbitrary tensors; for tensors of order greater than 2 (matrices are order 2 tensors), rank is very hard to compute, unlike for matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] There is a notion of rank for smooth maps between smooth manifolds.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] It is equal to the linear rank of the derivative.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Matrix rank should not be confused with tensor order, which is called tensor rank.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] Tensor order is the number of indices required to write a tensor, and thus matrices all have tensor order 2.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] More precisely, matrices are tensors of type (1,1), having one row index and one column index, also called covariant order 1 and contravariant order 1; see Tensor (intrinsic definition) for details.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/rank-linear-algebra] The tensor rank of a matrix can also mean the minimum number of simple tensors necessary to express the matrix as a linear combination, and that this definition does agree with matrix rank as here discussed.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In linear algebra, the **singular value decomposition** (**SVD**) is a factorization of a real or complex matrix into a rotation, followed by a scaling, followed by another rotation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It generalizes the eigendecomposition of a square normal matrix with an orthonormal eigenbasis to any ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is related to the polar decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Such decompositions always exist for any complex matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is real, then ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ can be guaranteed to be real orthogonal matrices; in such contexts, the SVD is often denoted ⁠ $\mathbf {U\Sigma V} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The diagonal entries $\sigma _{i}=\mathbf {\Sigma } _{ii}$ of $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ are uniquely determined by ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ up to reordering and are known as the singular values of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The number of non-zero singular values is equal to the rank of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and the columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ are called left-singular vectors and right-singular vectors of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠, respectively.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] However, it is always possible to choose the decomposition such that the singular values $\mathbf {\Sigma } _{ii}$ are in descending order.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In this case, $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ (but not ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠) is uniquely determined by ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Mathematical applications of the SVD include computing the pseudoinverse, matrix approximation, and determining the rank, range, and null space of a matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD is also extremely useful in many areas of science, engineering, and statistics, such as signal processing, least squares fitting of data, and process control.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In the special case when ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is an ⁠ $m\times m$ ⁠ real square matrix, the matrices ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ can be chosen to be real ⁠ $m\times m$ ⁠ matrices too.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In that case, "unitary" is the same as "orthogonal".
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In particular, if ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ has a positive determinant, then ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ can be chosen to be both rotations with reflections, or both rotations without reflections.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If the determinant is negative, exactly one of them will have a reflection.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If the determinant is zero, each can be independently chosen to be of either type.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If the matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is real but not square, namely ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ with ⁠ $m\neq n$ ⁠, it can be interpreted as a linear transformation from ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠ to ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As shown in the figure, the singular values can be interpreted as the magnitude of the semiaxes of an ellipse in 2D.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This concept can be generalized to ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional Euclidean space, with the singular values of any ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ square matrix being viewed as the magnitude of the semiaxis of an ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional ellipsoid.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Similarly, the singular values of any ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ matrix can be viewed as the magnitude of the semiaxis of an ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional ellipsoid in ⁠ m ⁠-dimensional space, for example as an ellipse in a (tilted) 2D plane in a 3D space.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Singular values encode magnitude of the semiaxis, while singular vectors encode direction.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Since ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ are unitary, the columns of each of them form a set of orthonormal vectors, which can be regarded as basis vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ maps the basis vector ⁠ $\mathbf {V} _{i}$ ⁠ to the stretched unit vector ⁠ $\sigma _{i}\mathbf {U} _{i}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] By the definition of a unitary matrix, the same is true for their conjugate transposes ⁠ $\mathbf {U} ^{*}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠, except the geometric interpretation of the singular values as stretches is lost.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] When ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is a positive-semidefinite Hermitian matrix, ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ are both equal to the unitary matrix used to diagonalize ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] However, when ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is not positive-semidefinite and Hermitian but still diagonalizable, its eigendecomposition and singular value decomposition are distinct.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] With respect to these bases, the map ⁠ T ⁠ is therefore represented by a diagonal matrix with non-negative real diagonal entries.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] To get a more visual flavor of singular values and SVD factorization – at least when working on real vector spaces – consider the sphere ⁠ S ⁠ of radius one in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The linear map ⁠ T ⁠ maps this sphere onto an ellipsoid in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Non-zero singular values are simply the lengths of the semi-axes of this ellipsoid.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] These directions happen to be mutually orthogonal.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Apply first an isometry ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ sending these directions to the coordinate axes of ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] On a second move, apply an endomorphism ⁠ $\mathbf {D}$ ⁠ diagonalized along the coordinate axes and stretching or shrinking in each direction, using the semi-axis lengths of ⁠ $T(S)$ ⁠ as scaling coefficients.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The composition ⁠ $\mathbf {D} \circ \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ then sends the unit-sphere onto an ellipsoid isometric to ⁠ $T(S)$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] To define the third and last move, apply an isometry ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ to this ellipsoid to obtain ⁠ $T(S)$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As can be easily checked, the composition ⁠ $\mathbf {U} \circ \mathbf {D} \circ \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ coincides with ⁠ T ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The singular values of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ are the diagonal entries of ⁠ $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ ⁠: ${\color {PineGreen}3},{\color {BrickRed}{\sqrt {5}}},{\color {BlueViolet}2},{\color {CadetBlue}0}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The corresponding left- and right-singular vectors are the columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and rows of ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠, respectively.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ has rank ⁠ 3 ⁠, so there are only three non-zero singular values.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Likewise for the last column of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The vectors ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ are called **left-singular** and **right-singular vectors** for ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠, respectively.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In any singular value decomposition $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {U} \mathbf {\Sigma } \mathbf {V} ^{*},$ the diagonal entries of ⁠ $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ ⁠ are equal to the singular values of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The first ⁠ $p=\min\{m,n\}$ ⁠ columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ are, respectively, left- and right-singular vectors for the corresponding singular values.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A singular value for which we can find two left- (or right-) singular vectors that are linearly independent is called *degenerate*.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If ⁠ $\mathbf {u} _{1}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {u} _{2}$ ⁠ are two left-singular vectors which both correspond to the singular value ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠, then any normalized linear combination of the two vectors is also a left-singular vector corresponding to the singular value ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The similar statement is true for right-singular vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The numbers of independent left- and right-singular vectors coincide, and these singular vectors appear in the same columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠: those corresponding to the diagonal elements of ⁠ $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ ⁠ with the same value ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As an exception, the left- and right-singular vectors of singular value ⁠ 0 ⁠ comprise all unit vectors in the cokernel and kernel, respectively, of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] By the rank–nullity theorem, these subspaces cannot have the same dimension if ⁠ $m\neq n$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Even when all singular values are non-zero, if ⁠ $m>n$ ⁠, then the cokernel is non-trivial, in which case ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ is padded with ⁠ $m-n$ ⁠ orthogonal [orthonormal?] vectors from the cokernel.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Conversely, if ⁠ $m<n$ ⁠, then ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ is padded by ⁠ $n-m$ ⁠ orthogonal [orthonormal?] vectors from the kernel.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] However, if the singular value ⁠ 0 ⁠ exists, the extra columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ already appear as left- or right-singular vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Non-degenerate singular values always have unique left- and right-singular vectors, up to multiplication by a (unit) phase factor ⁠ $e^{i\varphi }$ ⁠ (for the real case, up to a sign).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In general, the SVD is unique up to arbitrary unitary transformations applied uniformly to the column vectors of both ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The singular value decomposition is very general in the sense that it can be applied to any ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ matrix, whereas eigenvalue decomposition can only be applied to square diagonalizable matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Nevertheless, the two decompositions are related.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The right-hand sides of these relations describe the eigenvalue decompositions of the left-hand sides.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] When ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is positive semi-definite, ⁠ $\sigma _{i}$ ⁠ will be non-negative real numbers so that the decomposition ⁠ $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {U} \mathbf {D} \mathbf {U} ^{*}$ ⁠ is also a singular value decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The singular value decomposition can be used for computing the pseudoinverse of a matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The pseudoinverse is one way to solve linear least squares problems.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A set of homogeneous linear equations can be written as ⁠ $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x} =\mathbf {0}$ ⁠ for a matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠, vector ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠, and zero vector ⁠ $\mathbf {0}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A typical situation is that ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠ is known and a non-zero ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ is to be determined which satisfies the equation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Such an ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ belongs to ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠'s null space and is sometimes called a (right) null vector of ⁠ $\mathbf {A} .$ ⁠ The vector ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ can be characterized as a right-singular vector corresponding to a singular value of ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠ that is zero.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This observation means that if ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠ is a square matrix and has no vanishing singular value, the equation has no non-zero ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ as a solution.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It also means that if there are several vanishing singular values, any linear combination of the corresponding right-singular vectors is a valid solution.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A total least squares problem seeks the vector ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ that minimizes the 2-norm of a vector ⁠ $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x}$ ⁠ under the constraint $\|\mathbf {x} \|=1.$ The solution turns out to be the right-singular vector of ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠ corresponding to the smallest singular value.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As a consequence, the rank of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ equals the number of non-zero singular values which is the same as the number of non-zero diagonal elements in $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In numerical linear algebra the singular values can be used to determine the *effective rank* of a matrix, as rounding error may lead to small but non-zero singular values in a rank deficient matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Singular values beyond a significant gap are assumed to be numerically equivalent to zero.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Some practical applications need to solve the problem of approximating a matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ with another matrix ${\tilde {\mathbf {M} }}$ , said to be truncated, which has a specific rank ⁠ r ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This is known as the **Eckart–Young theorem**, as it was proved by those two authors in 1936.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] One practical consequence of the low-rank approximation given by SVD is that a greyscale image represented as an $m\times n$ matrix $\mathbf {A}$ , can be efficiently represented by keeping the first k singular values and corresponding vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] $\mathbf {A} _{k}=\sum _{j=1}^{k}\sigma _{j}\mathbf {u} _{j}\mathbf {v} _{j}^{T}$ gives an image with the best 2-norm error out of all rank k approximations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Thus, the task becomes finding an approximation that balances retaining perceptual fidelity with the number of vectors required to reconstruct the image.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Storing $\mathbf {A} _{k}$ requires only $k(n+m+1)$ floating-point numbers compared to $nm$ integers.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This same idea extends to color images by applying this operation to each channel or stacking the channels into one matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Since the singular values of most natural images decay quickly, most of their variance is often captured by a small k .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] For a 1528 × 1225 greyscale image, we can achieve a relative error of $.7\%$ with as little as $k=100$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In practice, however, computing the SVD can be too computationally expensive and the resulting compression is typically less storage efficient than a specialized algorithm such as JPEG.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD can be thought of as decomposing a matrix into a weighted, ordered sum of separable matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Here ⁠ $\mathbf {U} _{i}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} _{i}$ ⁠ are the ⁠ i ⁠-th columns of the corresponding SVD matrices, ⁠ $\sigma _{i}$ ⁠ are the ordered singular values, and each ⁠ $\mathbf {A} _{i}$ ⁠ is separable.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD can be used to find the decomposition of an image processing filter into separable horizontal and vertical filters.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Note that the number of non-zero ⁠ $\sigma _{i}$ ⁠ is exactly the rank of the matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Separable models often arise in biological systems, and the SVD factorization is useful to analyze such systems.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] For example, some visual area V1 simple cells' receptive fields can be well described by a Gabor filter in the space domain multiplied by a modulation function in the time domain.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Thus, given a linear filter evaluated through, for example, reverse correlation, one can rearrange the two spatial dimensions into one dimension, thus yielding a two-dimensional filter (space, time) which can be decomposed through SVD.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The first column of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ in the SVD factorization is then a Gabor while the first column of ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ represents the time modulation (or vice versa).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] which is the fraction of the power in the matrix M which is accounted for by the first separable matrix in the decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Equivalently, the solution is the unitary matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {R} =\mathbf {U} \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ of the Polar Decomposition $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {R} \mathbf {P} =\mathbf {P} '\mathbf {R}$ in either order of stretch and rotation, as described above.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This problem is equivalent to finding the nearest orthogonal matrix to a given matrix $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {A} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {B}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The Kabsch algorithm (called Wahba's problem in other fields) uses SVD to compute the optimal rotation (with respect to least-squares minimization) that will align a set of points with a corresponding set of points.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is used, among other applications, to compare the structures of molecules.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Let $\mathbf {X} \in \mathbb {R} ^{N\times p}$ be a data matrix where each of the N rows is a (feature-wise) mean-centered observation, each of dimension p .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] We see that $\mathbf {V} {\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ contains the scores of the rows of $\mathbf {X}$ (i.e. each observation), and $\mathbf {U}$ is the matrix whose columns are principal component loading vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD and pseudoinverse have been successfully applied to signal processing, image processing and big data (e.g., in genomic signal processing).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD is also applied extensively to the study of linear inverse problems and is useful in the analysis of regularization methods such as that of Tikhonov.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is widely used in statistics, where it is related to principal component analysis and to correspondence analysis, and in signal processing and pattern recognition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is also used in output-only modal analysis, where the non-scaled mode shapes can be determined from the singular vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Yet another usage is latent semantic indexing in natural-language text processing.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In general numerical computation involving linear or linearized systems, there is a universal constant that characterizes the regularity or singularity of a problem, which is the system's "condition number" $\kappa :=\sigma _{\text{max}}/\sigma _{\text{min}}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It often controls the error rate or convergence rate of a given computational scheme on such systems.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD also plays a crucial role in the field of quantum information, in a form often referred to as the Schmidt decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Through it, states of two quantum systems are naturally decomposed, providing a necessary and sufficient condition for them to be entangled: if the rank of the $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ matrix is larger than one.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The output singular vectors in this case are entire weather systems.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] These perturbations are then run through the full nonlinear model to generate an ensemble forecast, giving a handle on some of the uncertainty that should be allowed for around the current central prediction.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] SVD has also been applied to reduced order modelling.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The aim of reduced order modelling is to reduce the number of degrees of freedom in a complex system which is to be modeled.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] SVD was coupled with radial basis functions to interpolate solutions to three-dimensional unsteady flow problems.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Interestingly, SVD has been used to improve gravitational waveform modeling by the ground-based gravitational-wave interferometer aLIGO.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] SVD can help to increase the accuracy and speed of waveform generation to support gravitational-waves searches and update two different waveform models.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Singular value decomposition is used in recommender systems to predict people's item ratings.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Distributed algorithms have been developed for the purpose of calculating the SVD on clusters of commodity machines.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Low-rank SVD has been applied for hotspot detection from spatiotemporal data with application to disease outbreak detection.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A combination of SVD and higher-order SVD also has been applied for real time event detection from complex data streams (multivariate data with space and time dimensions) in disease surveillance.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In astrodynamics, the SVD and its variants are used as an option to determine suitable maneuver directions for transfer trajectory design and orbital station-keeping.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD can be used to measure the similarity between real-valued matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] By measuring the angles between the singular vectors, the inherent two-dimensional structure of matrices is accounted for.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This method was shown to outperform cosine similarity and Frobenius norm in most cases, including brain activity measurements from neuroscience experiments.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] An eigenvalue ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ of a matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is characterized by the algebraic relation ⁠ $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {u} =\lambda \mathbf {u} .$ ⁠ When ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is Hermitian, a variational characterization is also available.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Let ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ be a real ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ symmetric matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The complex Hermitian case is similar; there ⁠ $f(\mathbf {x} )=\mathbf {x} ^{*}\mathbf {M} \mathbf {x}$ ⁠ is a real-valued function of ⁠ $2n$ ⁠ real variables.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Singular values are similar in that they can be described algebraically or from variational principles.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Although, unlike the eigenvalue case, Hermiticity, or symmetry, of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is no longer required.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This section gives these two arguments for existence of singular value decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Let $\mathbf {M}$ be an ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ complex matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Note that $\mathbf {V}$ is here by definition a matrix whose i -th column is the i -th eigenvector of $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ , corresponding to the eigenvalue ${\bar {\mathbf {D} }}_{ii}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Moreover, the j -th column of $\mathbf {V}$ , for $j>\ell$ , is an eigenvector of $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ with eigenvalue ${\bar {\mathbf {D} }}_{jj}=0$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Moreover, the second equation implies $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {V} _{2}=\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] since $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {V} _{2}=\mathbf {0} .$ This can be also seen as immediate consequence of the fact that $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {V} _{1}\mathbf {V} _{1}^{*}=\mathbf {M}$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] We see that this is almost the desired result, except that $\mathbf {U} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {V} _{1}$ are in general not unitary, since they might not be square.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, we do know that the number of rows of $\mathbf {U} _{1}$ is no smaller than the number of columns, since the dimensions of $\mathbf {D}$ is no greater than m and n .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This means that we can choose $\mathbf {U} _{2}$ such that $\mathbf {U} ={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {U} _{1}&\mathbf {U} _{2}\end{bmatrix}}$ is unitary.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] For ⁠ $\mathbf {V} _{1}$ ⁠ we already have ⁠ $\mathbf {V} _{2}$ ⁠ to make it unitary.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] where extra zero rows are added **or removed** to make the number of zero rows equal the number of columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U} _{2},$ ⁠ and hence the overall dimensions of $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ equal to $m\times n$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Notice the argument could begin with diagonalizing ⁠ $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {M} ^{*}$ ⁠ rather than ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ (This shows directly that ⁠ $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {M} ^{*}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ have the same non-zero eigenvalues).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular values can also be characterized as the maxima of ⁠ $\mathbf {u} ^{\mathrm {T} }\mathbf {M} \mathbf {v} ,$ ⁠ considered as a function of ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v} ,$ ⁠ over particular subspaces.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular vectors are the values of ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ where these maxima are attained.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Let ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ denote an ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ matrix with real entries.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Consider the function ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠ restricted to ⁠ $S^{m-1}\times S^{n-1}.$ ⁠ Since both ⁠ $S^{m-1}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $S^{n-1}$ ⁠ are compact sets, their product is also compact.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If it were negative, changing the sign of either ⁠ $\mathbf {u} _{1}$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\mathbf {v} _{1}$ ⁠ would make it positive and therefore larger.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] More singular vectors and singular values can be found by maximizing ⁠ $\sigma (\mathbf {u} ,\mathbf {v} )$ ⁠ over normalized ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ which are orthogonal to ⁠ $\mathbf {u} _{1}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v} _{1},$ ⁠ respectively.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The passage from real to complex is similar to the eigenvalue case.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] One-sided Jacobi algorithm is an iterative algorithm, where a matrix is iteratively transformed into a matrix with orthogonal columns.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The elementary iteration is given as a Jacobi rotation, $M\leftarrow MJ(p,q,\theta ),$ where the angle $\theta$ of the Jacobi rotation matrix $J(p,q,\theta )$ is chosen such that after the rotation the columns with numbers p and q become orthogonal.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The indices $(p,q)$ are swept cyclically, $(p=1\dots m,q=p+1\dots m)$ , where m is the number of columns.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Two-sided Jacobi SVD algorithm—a generalization of the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm—is an iterative algorithm where a square matrix is iteratively transformed into a diagonal matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If the matrix is not square the QR decomposition is performed first and then the algorithm is applied to the R matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The iterations proceeds exactly as in the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm: by cyclic sweeps over all off-diagonal elements.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] After the algorithm has converged the resulting diagonal matrix contains the singular values.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The SVD of a matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is typically computed by a two-step procedure.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In the first step, the matrix is reduced to a bidiagonal matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This takes order ⁠ $O(mn^{2})$ ⁠ floating-point operations (*flop*), assuming that ⁠ $m\geq n.$ ⁠ The second step is to compute the SVD of the bidiagonal matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This step can only be done with an iterative method (as with eigenvalue algorithms).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, in practice it suffices to compute the SVD up to a certain precision, like the machine epsilon.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If this precision is considered constant, then the second step takes ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ iterations, each costing ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ flops.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Thus, the first step is more expensive, and the overall cost is ⁠ $O(mn^{2})$ ⁠ flops.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The first step can be done using Householder reflections for a cost of ⁠ $4mn^{2}-4n^{3}/3$ ⁠ flops, assuming that only the singular values are needed and not the singular vectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If ⁠ m ⁠ is much larger than ⁠ n ⁠ then it is advantageous to first reduce the matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ to a triangular matrix with the QR decomposition and then use Householder reflections to further reduce the matrix to bidiagonal form; the combined cost is ⁠ $2mn^{2}+2n^{3}$ ⁠ flops.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The second step can be done by a variant of the QR algorithm for the computation of eigenvalues, which was first described by Golub and Kahan in 1965.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The LAPACK subroutine `DBDSQR` implements this iterative method, with some modifications to cover the case where the singular values are very small.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Together with a first step using Householder reflections and, if appropriate, QR decomposition, this forms the `DGESVD` routine for the computation of the singular value decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The same algorithm is implemented in the GNU Scientific Library (GSL).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The GSL also offers an alternative method that uses a one-sided Jacobi orthogonalization in step 2.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This method computes the SVD of the bidiagonal matrix by solving a sequence of ⁠ $2\times 2$ ⁠ SVD problems, similar to how the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm solves a sequence of ⁠ $2\times 2$ ⁠ eigenvalue methods.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Yet another method for step 2 uses the idea of divide-and-conquer eigenvalue algorithms.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] There is an alternative way that does not explicitly use the eigenvalue decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The approaches that use eigenvalue decompositions are based on the QR algorithm, which is well-developed to be stable and fast.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Note that the singular values are real and right- and left- singular vectors are not required to form similarity transformations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] One can iteratively alternate between the QR decomposition and the LQ decomposition to find the real diagonal Hermitian matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Eventually, this iteration between QR decomposition and LQ decomposition produces left- and right- unitary singular matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This approach cannot readily be accelerated, as the QR algorithm can with spectral shifts or deflation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This is because the shift method is not easily defined without using similarity transformations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, this iterative approach is very simple to implement, so is a good choice when speed does not matter.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This method also provides insight into how purely orthogonal/unitary transformations can obtain the SVD.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The methods above yield ⁠ $O(mn^{2})$ ⁠ algorithms for the SVD of an $m\times n$ matrix M where $m\geq n$ .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Demmel, Dumitriu and Holtz show that for a symmetric M (i.e. $m=n$ ) the SVD can normwise stably be computed in $O(n^{\omega +\eta })$ arithmetic operations where $\omega$ is the matrix multiplication exponent and $\eta >0$ is any constant, i.e. essentially in matrix multiplication time.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular values of a ⁠ $2\times 2$ ⁠ matrix can be found analytically.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] where $z_{i}\in \mathbb {C}$ are complex numbers that parameterize the matrix, ⁠ $\mathbf {I}$ ⁠ is the identity matrix, and $\sigma _{i}$ denote the Pauli matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In applications it is quite unusual for the full SVD, including a full unitary decomposition of the null-space of the matrix, to be required.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Instead, it is often sufficient (as well as faster, and more economical for storage) to compute a reduced version of the SVD.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The thin SVD uses significantly less space and computation time if ⁠ $k\ll \max(m,n).$ ⁠ The first stage in its calculation will usually be a QR decomposition of ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ,$ ⁠ which can make for a significantly quicker calculation in this case.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Only the ⁠ r ⁠ column vectors of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ r ⁠ row vectors of ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ corresponding to the non-zero singular values ⁠ $\mathbf {\Sigma } _{r}$ ⁠ are calculated.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The remaining vectors of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ are not calculated.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In many applications the number ⁠ r ⁠ of the non-zero singular values is large making even the Compact SVD impractical to compute.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In such cases, the smallest singular values may need to be truncated to compute only ⁠ $t\ll r$ ⁠ non-zero singular values.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This can be much quicker and more economical than the compact SVD if ⁠ $t\ll r,$ ⁠ but requires a completely different toolset of numerical solvers.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In applications that require an approximation to the Moore–Penrose inverse of the matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ,$ ⁠ the smallest singular values of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ are of interest, which are more challenging to compute compared to the largest ones.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Truncated SVD is employed in latent semantic indexing.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] For this reason, it is also called the operator 2-norm.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] One can easily verify the relationship between the Ky Fan 1-norm and singular values.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The last of the Ky Fan norms, the sum of all singular values, is the trace norm (also known as the 'nuclear norm'), defined by $\|\mathbf {M} \|=\operatorname {Tr} (\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M} )^{1/2}$ (the eigenvalues of ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ are the squares of the singular values).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular values are related to another norm on the space of operators.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In addition, the Frobenius norm and the trace norm (the nuclear norm) are special cases of the Schatten norm.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This can be shown by mimicking the linear algebraic argument for the matrix case above. ⁠ $\mathbf {V} T_{f}\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ is the unique positive square root of ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M} ,$ ⁠ as given by the Borel functional calculus for self-adjoint operators.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] and notice that ⁠ $\mathbf {U} \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ is still a partial isometry while ⁠ $\mathbf {V} T_{f}\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ is positive.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The notion of singular values and left/right-singular vectors can be extended to compact operator on Hilbert space as they have a discrete spectrum.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If ⁠ T ⁠ is compact, every non-zero ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ in its spectrum is an eigenvalue.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Furthermore, a compact self-adjoint operator can be diagonalized by its eigenvectors.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Applying the diagonalization result, the unitary image of its positive square root ⁠ $T_{f}$ ⁠ has a set of orthonormal eigenvectors ⁠ $\{e_{i}\}$ ⁠ corresponding to strictly positive eigenvalues ⁠ $\{\sigma _{i}\}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Compact operators on a Hilbert space are the closure of finite-rank operators in the uniform operator topology.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The above series expression gives an explicit such representation.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular value decomposition was originally developed by differential geometers, who wished to determine whether a real bilinear form could be made equal to another by independent orthogonal transformations of the two spaces it acts on.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Eugenio Beltrami and Camille Jordan discovered independently, in 1873 and 1874 respectively, that the singular values of the bilinear forms, represented as a matrix, form a complete set of invariants for bilinear forms under orthogonal substitutions.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] James Joseph Sylvester also arrived at the singular value decomposition for real square matrices in 1889, apparently independently of both Beltrami and Jordan.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Sylvester called the singular values the *canonical multipliers* of the matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {A} .$ ⁠ The fourth mathematician to discover the singular value decomposition independently is Autonne in 1915, who arrived at it via the polar decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The first proof of the singular value decomposition for rectangular and complex matrices seems to be by Carl Eckart and Gale J.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Young in 1936; they saw it as a generalization of the principal axis transformation for Hermitian matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In 1907, Erhard Schmidt defined an analog of singular values for integral operators (which are compact, under some weak technical assumptions); it seems he was unaware of the parallel work on singular values of finite matrices.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This theory was further developed by Émile Picard in 1910, who is the first to call the numbers $\sigma _{k}$ *singular values* (or in French, *valeurs singulières*).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Practical methods for computing the SVD date back to Kogbetliantz in 1954–1955 and Hestenes in 1958, resembling closely the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm, which uses plane rotations or Givens rotations.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, these were replaced by the method of Gene Golub and William Kahan published in 1965, which uses Householder transformations or reflections.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In 1970, Golub and Christian Reinsch published a variant of the Golub/Kahan algorithm that is still the one most-used today.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] The singular values are non-negative real numbers, usually listed in decreasing order ⁠ ${\big (}\sigma _{1}(T)\geq \sigma _{2}(T)\geq \dots {\big )}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] The largest singular value $\sigma _{1}(T)$ is equal to the operator norm of T (see Min-max theorem).
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] The singular values are the absolute values of the eigenvalues of a normal matrix ⁠ A ⁠, because the spectral theorem can be applied to obtain unitary diagonalization of A as ⁠ $A=U\varLambda \,U^{*}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] Most norms on Hilbert space operators studied are defined using singular values.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] For example, the Ky Fan ⁠ k ⁠-norm is the sum of first k singular values, the trace norm is the sum of all singular values, and the Schatten norm is the ⁠ p ⁠-th root of the sum of the ⁠ p ⁠-th powers of the singular values.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] Note that each norm is defined only on a special class of operators, hence singular values can be useful in classifying different operators.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] In the finite-dimensional case, a matrix can always be decomposed in the form ⁠ $\mathbf {U\Sigma V^{*}}$ ⁠, where $\mathbf {U}$ and $\mathbf {V^{*}}$ are unitary matrices and $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ is a rectangular diagonal matrix with the singular values lying on the diagonal.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] This is the singular value decomposition.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] If $A^{*}A$ has full rank, the product of singular values is ⁠ $\det {\sqrt {A^{*}A}}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] If $AA^{*}$ has full rank, the product of singular values is ⁠ $\det {\sqrt {AA^{*}}}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] If A is square and has full rank, the product of singular values is ⁠ $\vert \!\det A\vert$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] If A is normal, then ⁠ $\sigma _{i}(A)=\vert \lambda _{i}(A)\vert$ ⁠, that is, its singular values are the absolute values of its eigenvalues.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] For a generic rectangular matrix ⁠ A ⁠, let ${\textstyle {\tilde {A}}={\begin{bmatrix}0&A\\A^{*}&0\end{bmatrix}}}$ be its augmented matrix.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] It has eigenvalues ${\textstyle \pm \sigma _{i}(A)}$ (where the ${\textstyle \sigma _{i}(A)}$ are the singular values of ${\textstyle A}$ ) and the remaining eigenvalues are zero.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] Let ${\textstyle A=U\varSigma \,V^{*}}$ be the singular value decomposition, then the eigenvectors of ${\textstyle {\tilde {A}}}$ are ${\textstyle {\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {u} _{i}\\\pm \mathbf {v} _{i}\end{bmatrix}}}$ for ⁠ $\pm \sigma _{i}$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] The smallest singular value of a matrix ⁠ A ⁠ is ⁠ $\sigma _{\mathrm {n} }(A)$ ⁠.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] Intuitively, if ⁠ $\sigma _{\mathrm {n} }(A)$ ⁠ is small, then the rows of ⁠ A ⁠ are "almost" linearly dependent.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] If it is ⁠ $\sigma _{\mathrm {n} }(A)=0$ ⁠, then the rows of ⁠ A ⁠ are linearly dependent and ⁠ A ⁠ is not invertible.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] Let B denote A with two of its rows *and* columns deleted.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] Let B denote an $(m-k)\times (n-\ell )$ submatrix of A .
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] This concept was introduced by Erhard Schmidt in 1907.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] Schmidt called singular values "eigenvalues" at that time.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] The name "singular value" was first quoted by Smithies in 1937.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] This formulation made it possible to extend the notion of singular values to operators in Banach space.
[src:singular-value-decomposition-deep/singular-value] Note that there is a more general concept of *s-numbers*, which also includes Gelfand and Kolmogorov width.
